Go into EC2 instance connect ssh.
vim install.sh 
paste the code from install.sh
change the permission 
chmod 777 install.sh
run the script --->  ./install.sh
After the script is done, you can check if the application is running by using the command:
docker --version
kubectl version
kind version
You should see the versions of Docker, Kubernetes, and Kind displayed in the terminal. This indicates that the installation was successful and the tools are ready to use.

create configuration file of creating cluster
mkdir kind-cluster
cd kind-cluster
vim kind-config.yml
paste the code from  kind-config.yml
create the cluster from kind-config.yml using command :
kind create cluster --name=tws-cluster --config=kind-config.yaml
After the cluster is created, you can check the status of the cluster using the command:
kubectl cluster-info --context kind-tws-cluster
This command will display the cluster information, confirming that the cluster is up and running. You can also use the command:
kubectl get nodes
to see the nodes in the cluster and their status. If the nodes are listed and in a ready state, it means your Kubernetes cluster is successfully set up with Kind.
To deploy your application on the Kubernetes cluster, you can create a deployment file (e.g., deployment.yaml) and apply it using kubectl:
kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml